DOCUMENT();

loadMacros('PGstandard.pl', 'PGML.pl', 'parserGraphTool.pl',
  'contextFraction.pl','PGcourse.pl');

#  * availableTools: this determines which tools should be shown on the

Context('Fraction');

$x1 = random(-8, -4);
$x2 = non_zero_random(-3, -3);
$x3 = random(4, 8);

$y0 = non_zero_random(-3,3);

$k = Fraction($y0,-$x1*$x2*$x3);


$gt = GraphTool("{cubic, solid, ($x1, 0), ($x2, 0), ($x3, 0), (0, $y0)}")->with(
    bBox           => [ -11, 11, 11, -11 ],
    availableTools =>
        [ 'PointTool', 'LineTool', 'CircleTool', 'QuadraticTool', 'CubicTool', 'FillTool', 'SolidDashTool' ],
);

BEGIN_PGML
Graph the cubic function [``p(x) = [$k](x-[$x1])(x-[$x2])(x-[$x3])``]

[_]{$gt}
END_PGML

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
To graph the cubic, you'll need 4 points.  Because of the form, there are
3 zeros [`([$x1],0), ([$x2],0)`] and [`([$x3],0)`].  Any other point can be
chosen, but another easy one is the [`y`]-intercept, which by evaluating
[`p(0)=[$y0]`], then select [`(0,[$y0])`].

The solution is
[@ $gt->generateAnswerGraph @]*
END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();